{{Infobox officeholder |name = Edgar A. Sharp |image = Edgar A. Sharp (New York Congressman).jpg |state = [[New York (state)|New York]] |district = {{ushr|NY|1|1st}} |term_start = January 3, 1945 |term_end = January 3, 1947 |predecessor = [[Leonard W. Hall]] |successor = [[W. Kingsland Macy]] |office1 = [[town supervisor|Supervisor]] of the [[Town of Brookhaven, New York|Town of Brookhaven]] |term_start1 = January 1, 1935 |term_end1 = January 1, 1943 | birth_date={{birth date|1876|06|03}} | birth_place=[[Patchogue, New York]] | death_date= {{Death date and age|1948|11|27|1876|06|03}} | death_place=[[Patchogue, New York]] | party=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] | resting_place= [[Holy Sepulchre Cemetery (Coram, New York)]] }}
'''Edgar Allan Sharp''' (June 3, 1876 &ndash; November 27, 1948) was a [[United States House of Representatives|United States Representative]] from New York. Born in [[Patchogue, New York|Patchogue, Suffolk County]], he attended the public and high schools, engaged as a clerk in the post office at Patchogue from 1898 to 1906 and served as assistant [[postmaster]] from 1906 to 1918. He was in charge of construction work for the [[Knights of Columbus]] in France and England from April 1918 to January 1920 and engaged in the real estate and insurance business in Patchogue and as real estate appraiser for [[Suffolk County, New York|Suffolk County]] from 1920 to 1944. He was an [[auctioneer]] from 1929 to 1944 and was also interested in banking.
From 1930 to 1933, he was a member of the [[zoning]] and planning board of the [[Brookhaven, New York|Town of Brookhaven]] and was [[town supervisor|supervisor]] of Brookhaven from 1935 to 1943. Sharp was elected as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] to the Seventy-ninth Congress, holding office from January 3, 1945 to January 3, 1947. He was not a candidate for renomination in 1946 and resumed his former business pursuits; in 1948 he died in Patchogue. Interment was in Saint Frances Cemetery, Patchogue, New York.
