'''Omar Derdour''' ({{lang-ar|عمر دردور}}), full name '''Abou El Kacem Omar Derdour''' (13 October 1913 – 19 March 2009), was an Algerian Muslim leader, [[Algerian nationalism|nationalist]], and political worker. 

A disciple of [[Abdelhamid Ben Badis]], he was active in the Islamic reformation of Algeria and the [[Algerian War of Independence]]. He directed the [[Friends of the Manifesto and Liberty|Friends of the Manifesto and Liberty Party]]'s (in French: ''Amis du Manifeste et de la Liberté'', AML) Federation in [[Constantine, Algeria|Constantine]], and was a member of the Central Committee and Deputy of the Constantine region from 1947 to 1951. 

In 1954, Omar Derdour became a political worker within the [[National Liberation Front (Algeria)|National Liberation Front]] (FLN) and undertook a great deal of propaganda and mobilization in France in 1955 and 1956 and then in [[Cairo]], Egypt and throughout the Arab world. After independence, Omar Derdour devoted himself to teaching, became a founding member of the Islamic Institute, and founded numerous other Muslim institutions and schools.

== Early years==
Derdour was born on 13 October 1913 in [[Hidoussa]], a small village in the municipality of [[Teniet El Abed]], in the heart of the [[Aurès Mountains]]. He was born into a family of scholars which hailed from the [[Ouled Abdi Valley]] in that mountain region.{{sfn|Bouseloua|Guerfi|Mokhtari|Thiriez|2011|p=64}} The village lies   He learned the [[Quran]] in his great-grandfather's [[Zawiya (institution)|zawiya]] (a [[Maghrebi]] Islamic school).{{sfn|Le parcours de Cheikh Omar Derdour étudié}} Derdour went to [[Tolga, Algeria|Tolga]] where he studied at the school of Sheikh Ali bin Omar for two years, and was given a thorough Islamic education in language and jurisprudence.{{sfn|Obituary - Sheikh Omar}}

In 1932 Sheikh Abdul Hafiz al-Hashemi took Omar Derdour to [[Constantine, Algeria|Constantine]] and introduced him to Sheikh Imam [[Abdelhamid Ben Badis]], who agreed to accept him as a pupil on the condition that he passed an examination.{{sfn|Obituary - Sheikh Omar}}  In 1933 Derdour joined the "Green Mosque" (''Djamâa El Akhdar'') and began studying under Sheikh Abdelhamid Ben Badis. He would remain there for seven years.{{sfn|Le parcours de Cheikh Omar Derdour étudié}} In 1934, Ben Badis appointed Derdour teacher in the two mosques of ''Sidi Guemouche'' and ''Sidi Boumaâza'' in Constantine. In 1936, he became the close assistant of Ben Badis in organizing the courses.{{sfn|Bouseloua|Guerfi|Mokhtari|Thiriez|2011|p=64}}

== Return to Hidoussa==

In 1936 Omar Derdour and a group of fellow students founded a division of the Algerian Muslim Scholars Association and became active in education in the fields of religious and national awareness.{{sfn|Obituary - Sheikh Omar}} In 1937, Derdour returned to his village to establish a [[madrasa]] for the education of children and adults.{{sfn|Bouseloua|Guerfi|Mokhtari|Thiriez|2011|p=64}} Ben Badis considered him the "soul of the Islahiste{{efn|The Islahiste movement was a reform movement, which among other things gave women a greater role in religious matters.{{sfn|Barrak|Muller|1996|p=102}}}} movement in the Aures".{{sfn|Le parcours de Cheikh Omar Derdour étudié}} At the end of 1937, the French authorities became aware of his activities and imprisoned him in [[Batna, Algeria|Batna]] for "inciting the population to civil disobedience".{{sfn|Ghrib|2009}} Derdour was released on 6 January 1938, but was imprisoned a second time in August 1939 to complete his four-month sentence and was fined 8,000 francs. He was released in September 1939 upon the outbreak of World War II (1939-1945).{{sfn|Sheikh Sidi Abu al-Qasim Omar}} During the war the authorities suppressed all political activities, and he was forced to limit himself to non-political education.{{sfn|Obituary - Sheikh Omar}}

==Struggle for independence ==
[[File:O. Derdour.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Derdour, second from the right]]
[[File:Oulama Algerien a Damas dans la maison de Cheikh El-Ketani.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Derdour, second from the left]]
Omar Derdour directed the [[Friends of the Manifesto and Liberty|AML Party]]'s Federation in Constantine, and was a member of the Central Committee and Deputy of the Constantine region from 1947 until 1951.{{sfn|Derradji|2002|p=577}} The purpose of the AML party was to publicize and defend the [[Manifest du Peuple Algerien]]; anti-French, it demanded equal rights for the Muslim population and an [[autonomy|autonomous]] Algeria federated with France, the colonial power.{{sfn|Bennett|2005|p=242}} Between July 1955 and January 1956 he lived in [[Vichy]], France, working with the [[National Liberation Front (Algeria)|National Liberation Front]] (FLN) on defining the objectives and approach of the revolution.{{sfn|Obituary - Sheikh Omar}} Derdour moved to Cairo, meeting Sheikh Mohammed Bashir Brahimi and other members of the Revolutionary Command.  He was given the task of travelling to the Arab countries to raise support for the Algerian revolution.{{sfn|Obituary - Sheikh Omar}}  Derdour was based in Cairo until he moved to [[Tunisia]] in 1960. He taught soldiers on the Algerian border until independence was achieved in 1962.{{sfn|Obituary - Sheikh Omar}}

==Independent Algeria==

After Algeria gained independence, Omar Derdour devoted himself to teaching Islam and Arabic. He founded the first Islamic institute in Batna in May 1963, followed by the creation of similar institutions in several cities across the country, reaching 10,000 students.{{sfn|Le parcours de Cheikh Omar Derdour étudié}} 
In 1981, Derdour was appointed director of the institute in [[Sidi Okba]] for training imams and regional inspectors of religious affairs in Batna, [[Khenchela]] and [[Oum El Bouaghi]], holding this position until his retirement.{{sfn|Bouseloua|Guerfi|Mokhtari|Thiriez|2011|p=65}} In 1986, Derdour was appointed regional inspector of Religious Affairs in [[Batna Province|Batna]] and [[Khenchela Province|Khenchela]] provinces.{{sfn|Obituary - Sheikh Omar}} In the 2000s he built a mosque and a zawiya in the locality of El Hamza in the municipality of [[Oued Taga]] and a school in the village of his birth.{{sfn|Bouseloua|Guerfi|Mokhtari|Thiriez|2011|p=65}} 

On 19 March 2009 Abou El Kacem Omar Derdour died after a long battle against the effects of a stroke.{{sfn|Bouseloua|Guerfi|Mokhtari|Thiriez|2011|p=65}} He was buried in [[Tazoult]].

